name: dataset-top
---

# Dataset — top / takeOrdered / countByValue

Three more terminal aggregations.

```scalascript
val xs = Dataset.of(5, 3, 8, 1, 4, 9, 2, 7, 6)

// top(n) — n largest, descending
println(xs.top(3).mkString(", "))

// takeOrdered(n) — n smallest, ascending
println(xs.takeOrdered(3).mkString(", "))

// top / takeOrdered with n > size — returns all, sorted
println(xs.top(20).mkString(", "))

// countByValue — frequency map
val words = Dataset.of("a", "b", "a", "c", "b", "a")
val freq  = words.countByValue()
// Use sorted iteration over keys for deterministic output
List("a", "b", "c").foreach(k => println(s"$k: ${freq(k)}"))

// countByValue on Int
val ints = Dataset.of(1, 2, 1, 3, 2, 1)
val ic   = ints.countByValue()
List(1, 2, 3).foreach(k => println(s"$k -> ${ic(k)}"))
```
